The paper deals with the analysis of a competitive diffusion game on social networks, which involves the spread of influence among nodes. This topic falls under the intersection of game theory, social networks, and graph theory. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.GT (Computer Science - Game Theory and Decision Science). The paper also discusses the utility of players in terms of graphical distances, which relates to the study of social influence and information diffusion, making cs.SI (Computer Science - Social and Information Networks) another likely category. The analysis of the game on general undirected networks involves computational complexity, which suggests cs.DM (Computer Science - Discrete Mathematics) as another possible category. The paper also discusses the utility of players in the context of Erdos-Renyi random graphs, which relates to the study of network models and algorithms, making cs.NE (Computer Science - Network and Communications) another possible category. Finally, the paper deals with the concept of social welfare and sub-modularity, which relates to the study of social choice and optimization, making cs.SOC (Computer Science - Social and Economic Networks) another possible category.
